Use ASP.NET Core's `WebApplicationFactory<T>` from the `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing` package. It spins up an in-memory test server — no real port, no real network — and gives you an `HttpClient` wired directly to your middleware pipeline.

**Example setup:**

```csharp
// MyMcpTests.cs
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing;
using System.Net.Http.Json;
using System.Text.Json;

public class McpIntegrationTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test-client", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2.0", body.GetProperty("jsonrpc").GetString());
        Assert.True(body.TryGetProperty("result", out _));
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- Install `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing` in your test project
- Make your `Program` class accessible (add `public partial class Program { }` or use `InternalsVisibleTo`)
- For **Streamable HTTP** (the current MCP HTTP transport), POST JSON-RPC to your MCP endpoint and read the response
- For **SSE-based transport**, use `HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead` and read the stream line-by-line to parse `data:` events
- Override services (e.g., swap real dependencies for fakes) via `factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))`

**Testing SSE streams:**

```csharp
[Fact]
public async Task ListTools_OverSse()
{
    var request = new HttpRequestMessage(HttpMethod.Post, "/mcp");
    request.Content = JsonContent.Create(new
    {
        jsonrpc = "2.0", id = 2, method = "tools/list"
    });

    var response = await _client.SendAsync(request,
        HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead);

    using var stream = await response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync();
    using var reader = new StreamReader(stream);

    string? line;
    while ((line = await reader.ReadLineAsync()) != null)
    {
        if (line.StartsWith("data: "))
        {
            var json = JsonDocument.Parse(line[6..]);
            // Assert on your tools/list result
            break;
        }
    }
}
```

This gives you full protocol-level coverage (JSON-RPC framing, headers, status codes, SSE streams) with the speed of an in-process call.
